🚨 Why TLE Happened?

Because of this line:

dq.contains(arr[i])
❌ contains() in Deque is O(n)

Internally it iterates through entire deque.

So your total complexity becomes:

For each element → O(k)
Total → O(n * k)

Worst case:

200000 * 100000 = 20,000,000,000 operations

💀 Impossible within time limit.

🔥 Why Small Tests Passed?

Because n was small (≤ 200).

Large input exposed your time complexity issue.

✅ Correct Efficient Approach (O(n))

Use Deque + HashSet

import java.util.*;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
        int n = sc.nextInt();
        int k = sc.nextInt();
        
        int arr[] = new int[n];
        for(int i = 0; i < n; i++){
            arr[i] = sc.nextInt();
        }

        Deque<Integer> dq = new ArrayDeque<>();
        HashSet<Integer> set = new HashSet<>();

        for(int i = 0; i < n; i++){

            if(!set.contains(arr[i])) {
                dq.addFirst(arr[i]);
                set.add(arr[i]);
            }

            if(dq.size() > k){
                int removed = dq.removeLast();
                set.remove(removed);
            }
        }

        System.out.println(dq.size());

        while(!dq.isEmpty()){
            System.out.print(dq.removeFirst() + " ");
        }
    }
}
🚀 Now Complexity
Operation	Time
set.contains	O(1)
add/remove deque	O(1)

Total:

O(n)

Even for 200000 → fast.
